---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import { withBase } from "../../utils/url";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Quickstart (DuckDB)"
  description="Zero-setup dbt-burla example running entirely on your laptop."
  lede="The absolute minimum — a dbt project with one Python model running against DuckDB, in-process, with no cluster or cloud setup. Perfect for your first run and for CI."
  prev={{ title: "All examples", href: withBase("/examples/") }}
  next={{ title: "Snowflake ML scoring", href: withBase("/examples/snowflake-ml-scoring/") }}
>
  <h2>Run it</h2>
  <Code code={`git clone https://github.com/Burla-Cloud/dbt-burla.git
cd dbt-burla/examples/01-quickstart-duckdb
pip install "dbt-burla[duckdb]"
dbt run --profiles-dir .`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <p>Three models run end-to-end:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><code>stg_orders.sql</code> — a SQL view over inline data</li>
    <li><code>enriched_orders.py</code> — a Python model that uses pandas to add computed columns</li>
    <li><code>order_summary.sql</code> — a downstream SQL aggregate</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Inspect the result:</p>
  <Code code={`duckdb warehouse.duckdb
> select * from main.enriched_orders order by id;
> select * from main.order_summary;`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h2>What's in it</h2>

  <h3>profiles.yml</h3>
  <Code code={`quickstart:
  target: dev
  outputs:
    dev:
      type: burla_duckdb
      path: ./warehouse.duckdb
      schema: main
      burla_fake: true          # run Python in-process; no cluster needed`} lang="yaml" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />
  <p>Flip <code>burla_fake: false</code> and add <code>burla_cluster_url</code> when you're ready to run against a real Burla cluster.</p>

  <h3>models/enriched_orders.py</h3>
  <Code code={`import pandas as pd


def model(dbt, session):
    dbt.config(
        materialized="table",
        burla_workers=8,
        burla_cpus_per_worker=1,
    )

    orders = dbt.ref("stg_orders")

    bucket_by_amount = pd.cut(
        orders["amount"],
        bins=[-1, 50, 200, float("inf")],
        labels=["small", "medium", "large"],
    )

    return orders.assign(
        amount_bucket=bucket_by_amount.astype(str),
        amount_cents=(orders["amount"] * 100).round().astype(int),
        is_us=orders["country"] == "US",
    )`} lang="python" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h3>models/order_summary.sql</h3>
  <Code code={`select
    country,
    amount_bucket,
    count(*)    as order_count,
    sum(amount) as total_amount
from {{ ref('enriched_orders') }}
group by 1, 2
order by country, amount_bucket`} lang="sql" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h2>Key takeaways</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Python models are just normal Python files with a <code>model(dbt, session)</code> function.</li>
    <li>Downstream SQL models <code>ref()</code> the Python model's output like any other table.</li>
    <li><code>burla_fake: true</code> runs the whole pipeline in-process — CI and local dev don't need a cluster.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
